  "prompt": "Is OBC quota applicable to those who sold their property?",
  "response": "The applicability of the Other Backward Classes (OBC) quota is typically determined based on the socioeconomic status of the individual or family rather than property ownership alone. Generally, the quota system aims to assist individuals from socially and educationally disadvantaged backgrounds. The criteria for eligibility are often based on annual family income, educational background, and other factors as prescribed by the government.\n\nIf an individual or family sells their property, it might impact their overall socioeconomic status, but it does not automatically disqualify them from the OBC quota. The key determinant is usually the annual family income, known as the \"creamy layer\" criteria, which sets an upper limit on income for eligibility.\n\nTo ensure eligibility, it is crucial to verify the specific guidelines set by the government or relevant authorities, as these may vary and can be subject to change. Consulting with legal or government officials, or checking the official notifications and circulars, will provide clarity on eligibility for the OBC quota under specific circumstances.",
